				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Drift...<a name="58944"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 25 04 1:08 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>
<br />
To compensate for the drift in an auto circle, as well as the initial off-set of the circle when the auto circle is initiated, I have found that taping the Ctrl. button works wonders.  To practice this safely in order to attain the feel for the technique simply go to any newbie area and agro all the newbie mobs.  Round them up into the standard AoE bundle but do not play any AoE songs, just use them to practice starting and maintaining your auto circle.  If you mess up and fall into melee range you will see a cluster of &lt;mob name tries to hit you but misses&gt;  flash onto your screen.  You know that this would just about kill you with normal exp giving mobs as they would have landed many stuning attacks on you, but here it only serves to show you that you messed up.  Do this while watching yourself from different camera angles to see how it looks and to discover what you like best as far as the view you use.  So there you are, a wonderful way to practice entering into and maintaining an AoE kite circle while not having to risk your well earned experience and levels.  
<br />
Best wishes,
<br />
   Movin Tarrget.</span></td>
